DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers fundamental objections to extended cognition, alternative
theoretical frameworks, and methodological limitations of offloading research.
The critique landscape divides into three main strands. First, internalist
objections from Adams, Aizawa, and Rupert challenge the conceptual coherence
of extended cognition, arguing that coupling between brain and environment does
not constitute cognitive extension (the "coupling-constitution fallacy") and
that there exists a "mark of the cognitive" restricting cognition to intrinsic
neural properties. Second, alternative 4E frameworks—particularly radical
enactivism and predictive processing—offer competing accounts that either reject
representational content entirely (Hutto & Myin) or locate cognitive boundaries
differently (Hohwy's internalist predictive processing). Third, methodological
critiques examine problems with empirical extended mind research: unclear
individuation criteria for cognitive systems, arbitrary stopping conditions for
what counts as "part of" cognition, and difficulties translating philosophical
theses into testable predictions.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
These critiques reveal fault lines in both philosophical foundations and
empirical operationalizations of extended cognition and offloading. The
internalist challenges directly target the conceptual machinery undergirding
offloading research (if coupling ≠ constitution, what does "offloading"
mean?). Alternative frameworks suggest extended mind may obscure more
fundamental issues about embodiment, action-perception loops, or prediction
error minimization. Methodological concerns about individuating extended
systems directly impact how offloading studies design experiments and
interpret results.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited coverage of recent (2020-2025) empirical challenges to extended
cognition research. Predictive processing literature is extensive but its
implications for extended mind debates remain underdeveloped in this search.
Three entries marked INCOMPLETE (no abstract available): Sprevak 2009
(functionalist critique), Di Paolo 2008 (enactivist alternative), Rupert 2021
(predictive processing and systems). These papers remain in bibliography but
synthesis agents should rely on notes rather than abstracts.
SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Organize around three critique types (conceptual/internalist, alternative
frameworks, methodological). For each, distinguish what's at stake: whether
extended mind is false, whether it's uninteresting, or whether it's
empirically untestable. Track how defenders respond—e.g., Clark's replies
to Adams & Aizawa evolve from 2005 to 2010.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Internalist/Mark of the Cognitive: 6 papers - Adams, Aizawa, Rupert arguing
  cognition requires intrinsic neural properties
- Functionalist Defense: 3 papers - Sprevak, Wheeler, Clark defending extended
  functionalism
- Enactivist Alternative: 4 papers - Hutto, Di Paolo, Thompson offering
  non-representational or autopoietic accounts
- Predictive Processing: 3 papers - Hohwy, Clark, Fabry on prediction error
  and boundaries
- Methodological Critique: 2 papers - Bukow, Brigard on individuation and
  system boundaries
